cinema and other fields, represented here by famous figures such as Brigitte Bardot, Johnny Hallyday or Jean-Luc Godard, and less conventionally treated areas of enquiry (politics [de Gaulle], literary [Françoise Sagan], and intellectual culture [Lévi-Strauss]) the reader is provided with a broad understanding of the mechanisms of popularity and success, and their cultural, social, and political roles. The picture that emerges shows that many cultural articulations remained or became identifiably "French," in spite of the American mass-culture origins of these social, economic, and cultural transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCelebritieszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aFame. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh1 aDine, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaffney, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaffney, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHolmes, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Diana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJohnson, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTinker, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiner, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745009840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857450098423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857450098/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL 